        "description": "100-500 μm diameter for cleaning; 200 μm recommended for GFRP to balance resolution for surface prep (fine detail) and coverage for larger areas, considering fiber weave (~10-20 μm fibers). Source: Equipment specifications from Coherent and Trumpf laser systems; industry practice for composite applications."
      },
      "frequency": {
        "min": 1,
        "max": 200,
        "value": 50,
        "unit": "kHz",
        "description": "10-100 kHz for cleaning applications; 50 kHz recommended for GFRP to achieve fast processing while limiting heat accumulation in low-conductivity matrix (trade-off: higher freq speeds up cleaning but risks thermal damage). Source: Academic literature, e.g., Palmieri et al. (2020) in Composites Part B on laser cleaning of GFRP, noting optimal rates for contamination removal."
      },
      "pulseWidth": {
        "min": 0.1,
        "max": 1000,
        "unit": "ns",
        "value": 20,
        "description": "Nanosecond regime (5-100 ns) typical for industrial 1064 nm cleaning of GFRP to minimize heat-affected zone (HAZ <50 μm); picosecond (ps) or femtosecond better for ultra-precision but costlier and less common industrially. 20 ns recommended for polymer sensitivity. Source: Laser physics research in Journal of Applied Physics (e.g., Anisimov et al., 2015) on ablation thresholds for fiber-reinforced polymers."
      },
      "scanSpeed": {
        "min": 10,
        "max": 5000,
        "value": 2000,
        "unit": "mm/s",
        "description": "Range for effective ablation of light contaminants (faster speeds) vs. heavy (slower); 2000 mm/s optimal for uniform cleaning on GFRP without excessive heat buildup due to low thermal conductivity (~0.5 W/m·K). Source: Industry standards from Laser Institute of America guidelines; equipment manuals (e.g., CleanLASER CL series) and case studies on polymer composites."
      },
      "passCount": {
        "min": 1,
        "max": 10,
        "value": 2,
        "unit": "passes",
        "description": "1-5 passes typical for complete removal; multi-pass (2 recommended) for GFRP to ensure thorough cleaning of layered contaminants without single-pass overheating, especially for industrial prep. Source: Industry case studies, e.g., Boeing and Airbus reports on laser cleaning of composites; process optimization in Journal of Cleaner Production (2019)."
      },
